  "observation": "Orchestrator THINK: 3 ideas generated.",
  "suggestion": "[social-psychology+attribution-theory+motivation+clinical-psychology] REFINEMENT — Causal Attribution Spine (Weiner 1985). Replace 'which need has highest free energy' as the primary prediction driver with Weiner's 3D attribution taxonomy: Locus (internal/external) × Stability (stable/unstable) × Controllability (controllable/uncontrollable). The 8-cell attribution cube maps deterministically to (emotion, behavior, rootCause) tuples with strong empirical support: internal+stable+uncontrollable→depression/shame, external+unstable+controllable→anger, internal+unstable+controllable→guilt, external+stable→learned helplessness. Implementation: (1) infer attribution vector from stimulus.type + context features via a lookup table, (2) look up canonical (emotion, behavior, rootCause) from the attribution cube, (3) use existing free energy computation as a precision/intensity modifier on the output. The rootCause field in the Response interface maps perfectly to Weiner's locus dimension. This is the most directly testable improvement — benchmarks describe real human behavior which is attribution-driven, not need-energy-driven. — Math: Attribution vector a = (locus ∈ {-1,+1}, stability ∈ {-1,+1}, control ∈ {-1,+1}) → 8-cell cube. Emotion = f(a) from empirical lookup. Intensity = FE_dominant_need × polyvagal_multiplier.; [hedonic-psychology+dynamical-systems+affective-neuroscience+prospect-theory] NEW — Emotional Velocity: Trajectory over Snapshot. The current model is stateless (pure snapshot). Add emotional_velocity = current_arousal − prior_arousal to the person struct and use it to modulate need priors. Humans respond to trajectory, not absolute state: 'things are getting worse' at arousal=0.5 feels more threatening than 'things are improving' at arousal=0.7 (hedonic adaptation, escalation effects, contrast effects — Kahneman 1992). Implementation: in the free energy computation, adjust each need's expected value by −(velocity × 0.3) when velocity is negative. Negative trajectory lowers expectations, increases surprise, amplifies free energy, producing stronger emotion and defensive behavior than the static arousal would predict. This explains why: sudden losses hurt more than equivalent gains, hope amplifies engagement, and despair collapses behavior even at moderate absolute states. — Math: expected_need_adjusted = expected_need − (velocity × 0.3 × sign(velocity<0)). FE = (observation − expected_adjusted)² × precision. Velocity = Δarousal/Δt approximated as person.arousal − mean(person.history_arousal).; [catastrophe-theory+dynamical-systems+clinical-psychology+computational-neuroscience] NEW — Psychological Phase Transitions (Catastrophe Theory). Inspired by René Thom's catastrophe theory: behavior is not a smooth function of state but undergoes discontinuous phase transitions at fold boundaries. Model 4 discrete psychological phases: EXPLORE (low arousal ≤0.3, safety met), ENGAGE (medium arousal 0.3–0.6, safety met), DEFEND (high arousal 0.6–0.8, safety threatened), COLLAPSE (arousal >0.8 OR safety need unmet with high precision). Each phase has a canonical (emotion_class, behavior_class, rootCause_template). The current attractor landscape already models basins — extend it by making phase boundaries explicit crisp thresholds rather than gradient fields. The fold catastrophe at the DEFEND→COLLAPSE boundary explains clinical thresholds: why people 'snap', why trauma responses are binary (fight/flight/freeze), why therapy must cross a discontinuous barrier to work. Implementation: add phaseClassify() before the free energy computation; the phase gates which needs are active AND which response templates are available. — Math: Phase = argmax{EXPLORE: σ(0.3−arousal)×safety_met, ENGAGE: σ(arousal−0.2)×σ(0.65−arousal), DEFEND: σ(arousal−0.55)×threat_present, COLLAPSE: σ(arousal−0.78)×(1−safety_met)}. Response constrained to phase-canonical template.",
